⏱️ **Big O Notation & Algorithmic Complexity**

**Big O Notation** is a mathematical representation of how the runtime or space requirements of an algorithm grow as the input size ($n$) increases.

### Core Time Complexities (Fastest to Slowest):

| Complexity | Name | Typical Code Example |
|---|---|---|
| **O(1)** | Constant | Accessing an array item by index (`arr[5]`) |
| **O(log n)** | Logarithmic | Binary search in a sorted array |
| **O(n)** | Linear | A single loop through an array (`for (let i = 0; i < n; i++)`) |
| **O(n log n)** | Linearithmic | Efficient sorting algorithms (Merge Sort, Quick Sort) |
| **O(n²)** | Quadratic | Nested loops (`for` inside a `for`) |
| **O(2^n)** | Exponential | Naive recursive Fibonacci calculator |

### Example Comparison (Linear vs Quadratic)
```javascript
// O(n) - Linear Time: Prints each item once
function printAll(arr) {
  arr.forEach(item => console.log(item));
}

// O(n²) - Quadratic Time: Prints combinations
function printPairs(arr) {
  arr.forEach(item1 => {
    arr.forEach(item2 => console.log(item1, item2));
  });
}
```

