🧱 **Software Design Patterns**

Design patterns are typical solutions to common problems in software design. They are templates rather than copy-paste code.

### 1. Singleton Pattern (Creational)
Guarantees that a class has **only one instance** and provides a global access point to it. Used for DB connections, loggers, or config stores.
```javascript
class DatabaseConnection {
  constructor() {
    if (DatabaseConnection.instance) return DatabaseConnection.instance;
    this.connection = this.connect();
    DatabaseConnection.instance = this;
  }
  connect() { /* db connection */ }
}
const db1 = new DatabaseConnection();
const db2 = new DatabaseConnection();
console.log(db1 === db2); // true!
```

### 2. Factory Pattern (Creational)
Provides an interface for creating objects in a superclass, but allows subclasses to alter the type of objects that will be created.

### 3. Observer Pattern (Behavioral)
Defines a subscription mechanism to notify multiple objects (listeners) about events that happen to the object they are observing (subject).

